Every year in sports, there are new stars that come out of nowhere. But this week, two big-name athletes fell from graces in different ways. Here are our hot takes from the week of sports.

1. Rowdy Ronda Rousey Romped: She can be beaten after all. After her three previous fights lasted a total of 1:04, Rousey was dropped 59 seconds into the second round of her fight with Holly Holm. It wasn't a fluke, either. Rousey was dominated from the beginning. She said she didn't want to get frustrated or she'd end up getting kicked in the head. Well, that's exactly what happened. Kudos to Holm for the victory.

2. Peyton Manning's not so good: Read that to the tune of "Chicken Parm it tastes so good." At least that will make you smile a bit. Manning broke Brett Favre's record for most career passing yards, but he'll remember Sunday's game against the Kansas City Chiefs as the game he got benched. He's looked bad all year, but he's officially done. He went 5-20 with four picks. On the season, he has nine touchdowns and 17 interceptions. In hindsight, it would have been nice if Manning retired after last year. But how do you walk away from 4,727 yards and 39 touchdowns just like that? Father Time catches up to everyone eventually.

3. Flightless birds: After losing to the New Jersey Devils 4-0 on Saturday night, the Pittsburgh Penguins let their emotions show. Star forward Evgeni Malkin talked to reporters following the game about what was wrong: "Everything. We don't play right, we don't work hard. I know it's tough right now, but I know we're mad at each other. We need to stop, look in the mirror…start working. We're not working." Don't think for once second that what Malkin said was taken out of context, either. He's a smart man, and he meant what he said. At 10-7 on the season, coach Mike Johnston should start looking for real estate elsewhere. He's as good as gone.

Did you know that there are actually two dates that celebrate V-J Day?

Following the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, Emperor Hirohito announced Japan's acceptance to the Potsdam Declaration and surrendered on August 15, 1945, effectively marking the end of World War II. However, the official surrender ceremony did not occur until over two weeks later, and thus President Truman marked September 2 as the official V-J Day.

Private John F. Gallagher was recognized August 4, 2015 at the Indiantown Gap National Cemetery after being killed aboard the USAT Dorchester on February 3, 1943. Gallagher was part of a secret operation that was destined for Greenland to build runways for planes that would be used to hunt U-boats. Ironically it was a U-boat that struck the Dorchester and sank her. Gallaghers body was never recovered. Michael K. Dakota - Lebanon Daily News

It's summer, and you know what that means: increased gas prices. Or does it?

According to a GasBuddy survey, the average retail gasoline prices in Pennsylvania have risen 1.6 cents per gallon in the past week, but don't be discouraged quite yet.

According to Patrick DeHaan, GasBuddy senior petroleum analyst, "this summer will be the cheapest at the pump across much of the U.S. since 2009...well below year ago levels" and predicts that "the national average will not breach $3/gal this summer."

The Historical Society has received several answers about the photo, but a definitive conclusion has not been reached. Mystery solved: The Lebanon County Historical Society Office has received quite a few calls and emails from Annville residents regarding the "Mystery" photo published March 17. The house featured is located at 539 W. Queen St., next to the Brandt Flour Mill.  It may have been built by Abraham Herr (1762-1812). It later became the home to the Bernardo family. When the photo was taken, it was the Stephen family's residence.  The major consensus was that the photo was taken a few days after Tropical Storm Agnes in June 1972, and according to Carol (Stephen) Stewart, the man in the photo next to the overturned car was her father.  The water reached nearly to the top of the 10-foot ceiling of their home, and the three car garage (not shown in the photo) was also destroyed.  Thanks to Anna Beatty, Mike Bowman, Mike Frattaroli, Dean Wolfe and many others for supplying information. http://goo.gl/ubdgpp

Mystery solved:  The Lebanon County Historical Society has heard from Marian Foltz, who has identified her father, Joseph H. Sprecher, in the 'Mystery' photo published Feb. 17. Sprecher is standing in the middle of the photo, with rolled up shirt sleeves and tie. He was the owner the Sprecher Service Station & Garage, and Diner on Route 72, three miles north of Lebanon. Sprecher started the automobile transportation business in 1932 and established the gas station in 1937. The diner, which is now Heisey's Diner, was built in 1941 (and was rebuilt in 1951 to include a dining room). The image was taken in the early 1940s. Foltz recalled working for her father during World War II. Foltz married Thomas B. Foltz, an educator, who passed away in 2014; they were married for 65 years. Only other men identified in the image were Ray Smith, fourth from the right, and Allen Herr, far right in suit and tie. Curtis Kreiser, Christine Rupert and others contributed to the correct information.

http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27580694/lebanon-county-mystery-photo-identified-sprecher-service-station

Mystery solved: The Lebanon County Historical Society has received some information regarding this photo that was published on Feb. 10. The occasion was the annual Lebanon County Boy Scout dinner in January 1937 at the Weimer Hotel at Ninth and Cumberland Streets.  The men in the photo were the first seven to be awarded the Silver Beaver Award by the Lebanon County Council. Seated are, from left, William H. Worrilow, Rev. J. Leonard Hynson, Rodney P. Steltz, standing from left, Luther Harpel, Clarence L. Rohrer, Joseph G. Brand and Mark R. Arnold. The following people contacted the Historical Society with information: Chuck and Charlotte Allwein; Norma and Mark R. Arnold III; John L. "Jack" Worrilow, former mayor of Lebanon; and Jim Foster, who was able to provide a definitive answer for the identity of all the men in the photo and remembers well the interior of the Weimer Hotel from when he was a young boy in the 1950s.
http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27534664/lebanon-county-history-mystery-solved

Mystery solved: This photo published Feb. 3 show the house owned by Mr. and Mrs. Joseph Bowman and it still stands on Oak Street in Lebanon. It was built in 1957 for the family by the builder Johnny Leffler in the Georgian Colonial style. The image shows the early days of the neighborhood, developed after the relocation of the fairgrounds and was possibly taken sometime in 1959.  he Bowman family sold the home in the late 1970s to John and Mary Lou Kelsey. Many thanks to the current owners, Fran and Herb Dengler, and the Bowmans' daughter, Diane Griffith, for the information. The Lebanon County Historical Society also heard from Dave Houser of Cleona. He started his landscaping career at age 14, cutting the lawn and doing other odd jobs for Joseph Bowman and other homes in the neighborhood. He fondly recalled Bowman's collection of antique automobiles. http://www.ldnews.com/local/ci_27490467/lebanon-county-history-mystery

It was 1960, and the Lebanon-based Liberty Fire Co. had the first engine on the scene of the massive San Giorgio Factory fire on the north side of town.

Firefighter Richard Bleistine, 27 at the time, tried to quell the flames when the doors exploded outward. It could have been the end of his career had someone not dragged him out of the suffocating smoke.

"To this day, I still don't know who it was who dragged me out of there," Bleistine said recently. "I almost lost my life that day."   Now 81, the 60-year member of Liberty has been named firefighter of the year.

Lindsay Fulk of Prismatic Ink Tattoo completed a tattoo for Matt Stoner of Fredericksburg of the ninja turtle Michelangelo. The tattoo, which took nearly two hours to complete, is special because the orange "mask" on Michelangelo represents support for Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder(ADHD), something Stoner's son, Malik, 8, suffers from. Stoner got the tattoo at Prismatic because Fulk is running her annual fundraiser for the American Cancer Society, which has raised almost $3,000 as it heads into its fourth year. Fulk will do ribbon tattoos or puzzle pieces (which support autism) starting at $30 with $10 going to the American Cancer Society. The fundraiser will run through November.

NADAL FAMILY FUNDRAISER

Be FIT with Sarah & Nikki raised $492 last night a fundraiser for the Amarilys Nadal and David Arnold family, who lost their young son Cristian Nadal in a crash on Route 422 in South Lebanon Township a few weeks ago. The three instructors at at Ebenezer Fire Hall were Sarah Wickenheiser, Nicole Zimmerman, and Adalice Burgos. Adalice is related to the family. About 40 people participated in the fundraiser. 

In addition to the Zumba and Yoga class, Amarilys Nadal's Relay for Life team, Crazies 4 Cure, stepped up and provided baked goods  for donations. 

Anyone interesting in donating to help the family can contribute to a bank account set up at M&T Bank (any branch) under the name "Cristian & Marissa Nadal and Alaina Arnold Fund."

A global retirement crisis is bearing down on workers of all ages.
Spawned years before the Great Recession and the 2008 financial meltdown, the crisis was significantly worsened by those twin traumas. It will play out for decades, and its consequences will be far-reaching. Many people will be forced to work well past the traditional retirement age of 65.

Do you overdo it on Christmas?

One reason we can keep putting away food at Christmas is a phenomenon called sensory specific satiety (SSS). We can have enough of one sort of food, but still have an appetite for something else. It lies at the root of the expression "pudding stomach". It is why the trend for small sharing plates is a restaurateur's dream and a slimmer's nightmare. It is why kids suddenly declare: "I don't like it," while eating a food they definitely like.
READ MORE: http://bit.ly/JHdi0V

Today's kids can't keep up with their parents. An analysis of studies on millions of children around the world finds they don't run as fast or as far as their parents did when they were young. On average, it takes children 90 seconds longer to run a mile than their counterparts did 30 years ago. Heart-related fitness has declined 5 percent per decade since 1975 for children ages 9 to 17.

Why can't we agree on a seemingly simple health precaution? Because, like everything, pricking comes with pros and cons. Despite the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recommendation that everyone over the age of 6 months get vaccinated against influenza, only 41 percent of adults and 56 percent of children actually receive the flu shot. COLUMN: According to the Pennsylvania Department of Health, the number of annually reported cases of Lyme Disease in the United States has increased about 25-fold since reporting began in 1982. Close to 4,000 Lyme Disease cases have been reported annually in Pennsylvania with the highest incidence of disease being located in the southeastern parts of the state. Researchers believe that only one in 10 cases are reported.

John Hershey of Palmyra places flags on an embankment Thursday along the main road into Indiantown Gap National Cemetery, East Hanover Township. The large flags along the Avenue of Flags are interment flags that were donated from families across the state who received them during the funeral service for their loved ones. The large flags will be on display until mid-November. The small flags were put out Wednesday and Thursday in time for the annual Memorial Day service at the cemetery, which will be held Sunday, May 26. They represent the military lives lost since Sept. 11, 2011. The mini-flag display will be presented until after Memorial Day. The cemetery's memorial council sought volunteers for the project, which is sponsored by the Navy Club USA and the Masonic Lodge Sojourners.

Palmyra Area Business Association members hung the first of its new banners in the borough Tuesday morning. Looking at the new banner in front of Comic and Paperback Books Plus store at Lincoln and Main streets are, front from left, banner printer Mary Blose, PABA Vice President Laura Leonard and PABA member Rosemary Minni, and rear from left, PABA members Kristine Warner, and Tony Rose, store owner Ralph Watts, PABA President Margie Yohn, borough council President Jane Quairoli and Mayor Fred Carpenter. Last year, PABA solicited businesses to purchase banners that would feature the business name. The banners line the downtown business district and replace outdated 250th anniversary banners. PABA sold almost 60 banners.

Despite the overcast sky, Wayne Brubaker of Mahantango Ent. Inc., a Perry County-based company specializing in used-tire removal and recycling, smiles as he tosses a pair of tires into a trailer at the Lebanon Valley Expo Center and Fairgrounds on Friday. His efforts were part of the county West Nile Surveillance Program's annual tire collection, designed to remove potential mosquito breeding grounds from the area. Since its inception in 2002, the collection has recycled more than 50,000, adding to the total on Friday. The tires are turned into playground mulch, running tracks and asphalt additive, coordinators say.

Nine-year-old Noah Kelley of Lebanon wields a butterfly net while prowling for ladybugs at the Lebanon home of his grandparents, where he found what he believes is a rare nine-spotted ladybug.

 Kelley has submitted a picture of what he and many others believe is an extremely rare nine-spotted ladybug to Cornell University's Lost Ladybug Project - a program attempting to identify and aid the shrinking population of native ladybugs in America. Cornell University is analyzing the photo now to determine the species of ladybug.

The project has gathered 17,570 photos of ladybugs from across the nation; less than 1 percent of them are of the nine-spotted variety.

U.S FIELD HOCKEY TEAM UPSETS ARGENTINA

Thanks to a sold defensive effort that included several key stops by American goalkeeper Amy Swensen, a Northern Lebanon grad, the U.S. upset second-ranked Argentina today in the London Olympics, 1-0. The win evens the U.S.'s record at 1-1 and greatly helps its chances of reaching the medal round. A reproduction print of the deposit check chocolate magnate Milton Hershey wrote to White Star Lines for passage on the Titanic's maiden voyage is displayed at The Hershey Story Museum, 63 W. Chocolate Ave. The museum created a Titanic exhibit to coincide with the 100th anniversary of the sinking of the Titanic. The British passenger liner sank in the North Atlantic Ocean on April 15, 1912 after hitting an iceberg during her maiden voyage from Southampton, England, to New York City. Hershey was not on the ship, having changed his travel plans at the last minute. More than 1,514 people died when the Titanic sank.

status_message: Firefighters from the Cleona Fire Co. splash through the swollen waters of the Quittapahilla Creek after a reported explosion at a pumping station late Friday morning in North Cornwall Township. The station sits feet from the Quittie, which has spilled over, at the end of Cleona Boulevard and near Wilshire Drive. Borough manager Kerry Rohland said a generator, put in use after the electricity was cut off from the station, overheated and blew. A temporary generator was to be used until the electricity was restored, which Rohland said would be before Saturday. The explosion was reported at 10:58 a.m. In addition to Cleona, crews from Annville Union Hose and Neversink fire companies, and First Aid and Safety Patrol and Central Medical Transport responded. (LEBANON DAILY NEWS - EARL BRIGHTBILL)

When Save Our Schools was formed in the summer of 2008, its major goal was to prevent Elco School District from closing Schaefferstown and Myerstown elementary schools.
